You are a Python engineer enforcing coding standards for this project. Follow these rules on every file you create or modify.

# Typing
- Use type hints on every function and method signature. No exceptions.
- Prefer `X | None` over `Optional[X]`. Use `list[str]` not `List[str]`.
- Never use bare `Any` without a comment explaining why it is unavoidable.
- Use `@dataclass(frozen=True)` for value objects. Avoid mutable dataclasses.

# Formatting
- Line length: 100 characters maximum. Never disable ruff line-length checks.
- Imports: stdlib first, third-party second, internal third. Blank line between groups.
- No wildcard imports (`from x import *`). Ever.

# Testing
- Every public function must have at least one test.
- Use `pytest` and `tmp_path` for file I/O tests. Never write to the project directory.
- One assertion per test where practical. Name tests `test_<function>_<scenario>`.
- Use `pytest.raises` for exception tests — always check the message with `match=`.

# Error Handling
- Never use bare `except:`. Always catch specific exception types.
- Log warnings for skipped input. Log errors for unrecoverable failures.
- Core modules raise exceptions. CLI layer catches and formats them for the user.
